item.title: U.S. Debates How Quickly It Can Reopen
item.description: Countries around the world, including the U.S., took tentative steps toward reopening from coronavirus lockdowns, as officials debated how quickly to remove restrictions amid uncertainty about when the worst of the pandemic would subside.

item.title: As Kim Jong Un Disappears, North Korea Watchers Advise Caution
item.description: The guessing game began when Mr. Kim missed the country’s most important holiday April 15, then ratcheted higher after a South Korean publication reported he had heart surgery.

item.title: Trump's New Arms-Control Envoy Has a Short Clock for an Uphill Deal
item.description: Marshall Billingslea is looking at major hurdles to obtaining a nuclear-arms-control agreement among the U.S., China and Russia.

item.title: China Seeks to Ease Medical Goods Shipment Delays With New Rule
item.description: China offered a new route for producers of medical goods to obtain export approval, a move that could help ease recent shipment delays of critical medical equipment to fight the coronavirus pandemic to the U.S. and other countries.

item.title: As Italy Looks to Ease Its Lockdown, Doubts Persist About Its Readiness
item.description: Even countries seen as pandemic-fighting models like Singapore and Hong Kong have seen new infections rise this month, showing the scale of the challenge for most European countries and the U.S. as they seek to reopen.

item.title: Boris Johnson Set to Return to Work After Recovery From Covid-19
item.description: The British prime minister goes back to work on Monday to face critical decisions over how and when to reopen the country’s paralyzed economy.

item.title: How Coronavirus Outmaneuvered France's Health-Care System
item.description: Nursing-home deaths of more than 9,000 is one of the highest such tolls of any country world-wide, as France failed to adequately safeguard the facilities and some emergency services refused hospital care to their residents.

item.title: Coronavirus Cancels India's Spring Weddings, Spreading Pain Widely
item.description: The new coronavirus has wreaked havoc on traditional spring weddings in India, where an estimated 12 million weddings a year costing $57 billion support millions of people.

item.title: The Coronavirus Has Made Even Beirut Go Quiet
item.description: Many expected Beirut to take a laid-back attitude about the pandemic. Now, army jeeps rumble through the streets at night to enforce a curfew.
